Good. Environment ready. Now the ADR first, before any code.  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/docs/adr/ADR-001-rate-limiter-design.md', content='# ADR-001: Rate Limiter Design\n\nStatus: Accepted\nDate: 2024-04-24\n\n## Context / problem statement\n\nWe need a rate limiter that works for:\n\n1. **Function-level enforcement** (decorators around expensive calls).\n2. **HTTP enforcement** via ASGI middleware (FastAPI / Starlette) that\n   attaches standard `X-RateLimit-*` and `Retry-After` headers.\n3. **Distributed deployment** across N processes / hosts behind a load\n   balancer, where any request for a given key may land on any worker.\n\nThe limiter must be:\n\n- Correct under concurrency: no "over-grant" beyond configured capacity\n  even with hundreds of simultaneous callers hitting the same key.\n- Cheap on the hot path: O(1) Redis round-trips per decision.\n- Pluggable: algorithm and backend chosen independently at\n  construction time.\n- Degradable: a transient Redis outage must not hard-fail the\n  application, but the operator must be able to pick the trade-off\n  (fail-open vs fail-closed).\n\nOut of scope for this ADR:\n\n- Cross-datacenter replication semantics (we assume a single Redis\n  primary for each keyspace; CRDT-based limiters are a different\n  project).\n- Tariff / quota billing (distinct problem; rate limiting here is\n  about protecting downstream services, not metering).\n- Pre-emptive client-side hinting (e.g. `X-RateLimit-Policy`\n  advertisement).\n\n## Algorithm: token bucket vs sliding window\n\nWe implement **both** because they solve different problems and the\nwrong choice causes real production pain:\n\n| property                  | Token bucket                            | Sliding window counter                     |\n|---------------------------|-----------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n| shape of traffic allowed  | smooth average, bursts up to `capacity` | strict rate over trailing `period`         |\n| fairness across ticks     | good — drift is absorbed by refill      | good — interpolated across two buckets     |\n| memory per key            | 2 floats (tokens, last_refill)          | 2 ints (prev_count, curr_count) + window id |\n| burstiness                | allows intentional burst                | smooths out bursts                         |\n| typical use               | API call throttling, queue ingress      | abuse / fraud prevention, login attempts   |\n\n### When each wins\n\n- **Token bucket** wins when you want to let clients *occasionally*\n  burst (e.g. a page that does 5 prefetches at once) but enforce a\n  sustainable average. It is also easier to reason about as a queue\n  admission control — `capacity` is a literal depth.\n- **Sliding window** wins when the invariant is "never more than N in\n  any `period`-long window". Classic example: SMS / email sends where\n  regulators or downstream providers enforce absolute rates. Token\n  bucket allows `2 * capacity` over a window boundary if you refill\n  faster than period; sliding window does not.\n\n## Sliding window: log vs counter\n\nChosen: **sliding window counter** (weighted average of the previous\nfull window and the current partial window).\n\nRejected: **sliding window log** (store a timestamp per request, count\nentries in `[now-period, now]`).\n\n### Tradeoffs\n\n- Log is *exactly* correct but O(N) memory per key where N is the\n  allowed rate. At 10k req/min per tenant the log explodes Redis\n  memory; also every decision is O(N) (`ZRANGEBYSCORE`, trim, count).\n- Counter is O(1) memory (two counters + one window stamp) and O(1)\n  per decision. It over- or under-estimates by at most a small error\n  term bounded by `capacity * (position_in_window)` when traffic is\n  unevenly distributed within the previous window. In practice the\n  error is <= a few percent and always in the same direction for a\n  given call pattern — which is acceptable, because a rate limiter is\n  not a bank.\n- The counter\'s approximation errs on the side of *admitting* when\n  traffic ramps up and *rejecting* when it ramps down. For abuse\n  prevention (the dominant use case) this is the right bias: short\n  sudden bursts are still caught.\n\nIf a caller needs exact log semantics they can subclass `RateLimiter`;\nthe backend protocol is general enough.\n\n## Redis concurrency model\n\nChosen: **Lua scripts** evaluated server-side via `EVALSHA`.\n\nRejected: `WATCH` / `MULTI` / `EXEC` optimistic transactions.\n\n### Why Lua\n\n1. **Atomicity for free.** Redis runs the entire script atomically; no\n   other command interleaves. Lost-update races are impossible by\n   construction.\n2. **One round-trip** per decision regardless of contention.\n   `WATCH` / `MULTI` / `EXEC` requires a retry loop on `WatchError`,\n   which under high contention on the same key degenerates to\n   livelock — precisely the pathological case a rate limiter must\n   survive.\n3. **Portable semantics.** The same script runs on Redis Cluster\n   provided all keys hash to the same slot (we only ever touch one\n   key per call, so this holds trivially).\n4. **Clock source is the server.** Lua\'s `redis.call(\'TIME\')` (or a\n   caller-supplied `now` argument) gives one authoritative clock,\n   eliminating cross-process skew within a single backend.\n\nDrawbacks of Lua that we accept:\n\n- Scripts must be short and non-blocking (ours are ~20 lines, O(1)).\n- Some managed Redis offerings restrict `EVAL`. For those we expose\n  `InMemoryBackend` plus a documented upgrade path; we do not build\n  a second WATCH/MULTI fallback in the initial version.\n- Scripts are cached by SHA1; on a cache miss we fall back to `EVAL`\n  once, then `EVALSHA` thereafter. `redis-py` handles this via its\n  `Script` helper.\n\n### Why not `WATCH` / `MULTI` / `EXEC`\n\nUnder high contention on the same key, every concurrent caller\n`WATCH`es the same key, one `EXEC` succeeds, the rest retry. With C\nconcurrent callers on a busy key, expected retries scale as O(C); tail\nlatency blows up and CPU work is duplicated both on client and server.\nA Lua script serializes on the server for free and returns a single\nanswer.\n\n## Clock-skew policy\n\nDistributed deployments will have clock skew between application\nhosts. Our policy:\n\n1. **The backend is the clock authority.** For `RedisBackend`, the\n   script is called with the current time passed as an argument; we\n   pass `redis.call(\'TIME\')` from inside Lua so every decision uses\n   Redis server time, not the caller\'s wall clock. All stored\n   timestamps are therefore on one monotonic-per-server axis.\n2. **The in-memory backend uses `time.monotonic()`** for the local\n   process — it can never be called from multiple hosts so skew is\n   undefined.\n3. **The limiter never trusts a stored timestamp that is in the\n   future relative to `now`.** If one appears (e.g. a failover to a\n   replica with an earlier clock), we clamp `elapsed = max(0, now -\n   last)` so the limiter degrades to "no refill this tick" rather\n   than silently handing out free tokens.\n4. **`reset_ts` returned to the caller is in seconds since epoch in\n   the backend\'s frame of reference.** Clients must treat it as\n   advisory; the authoritative answer is always a subsequent\n   `enforce()` call.\n\n## Degradation when Redis is unreachable\n\n- `RedisBackend` catches `redis.exceptions.RedisError` and\n  `ConnectionError` and delegates to a configurable policy:\n  `fail_open=True` (the default for middleware) admits the request\n  and sets `remaining=-1` so metrics can spot it; `fail_open=False`\n  rejects with `retry_after_ms = 1000`.\n- The decorator defaults to `fail_open=False` — a function wrapped in\n  `@rate_limit` that silently stops limiting during a Redis outage is\n  a footgun.\n- Failures are surfaced as log warnings at most once per backoff\n  window (60s by default) so a dead Redis does not flood logs.\n\n## Rejected alternatives\n\n1. **Leaky-bucket queue (actually buffer, not just limit).** Rejected\n   because a rate *limiter* returns an immediate yes/no; a queue is a\n   different component that belongs in front of a worker pool. A user\n   wanting leak-on-drain semantics can layer an async queue on top of\n   `TokenBucketLimiter` in 15 lines.\n2. **Per-process in-memory only, no Redis.** Rejected because the\n   requirements state *distributed*. N workers each with their own\n   bucket grant up to `N * capacity` — classic over-grant bug. We\n   keep `InMemoryBackend` only for single-process use and tests.\n3. **GCRA (generic cell rate algorithm).** Considered — it is elegant\n   and gives token-bucket semantics with a single stored float\n   (`theoretical_arrival_time`). Rejected for the first cut because\n   (a) it is less familiar to operators reading dashboards, and (b)\n   `TokenBucketLimiter` is easy to explain and debug. GCRA may be\n   added later as a third algorithm without changing the public API.\n4. **Sharded counters with periodic reconciliation.** Considered for\n   very high QPS (>100k/s per key). Rejected as premature: a single\n   Redis primary handles ~100k EVALSHA/s on modern hardware, and\n   per-key hot-sharding is a different project (CRDT counters).\n')
Now the design doc, then implementation.  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/docs/design.md', content='# Design — `ratelimit`\n\n## Overview\n\n`ratelimit` is a distributed rate limiter packaged as a single Python\nmodule. It exposes two orthogonal axes:\n\n- **Algorithm** — how a decision is computed from state\n  (`TokenBucketLimiter`, `SlidingWindowLimiter`).\n- **Backend** — where state lives and how it is updated atomically\n  (`InMemoryBackend`, `RedisBackend`).\n\nThe public entry point is `limiter.enforce(key, cost=1)` which returns\na `Decision`. Two wrappers sit on top: `@rate_limit` for plain\ncallables and `RateLimitMiddleware` for ASGI apps.\n\n## Request flow\n\n```\n                ┌───────────────────────────┐\n  HTTP request  │   RateLimitMiddleware     │\n  ───────────▶  │  (ASGI)                   │\n                │                           │\n                │  1. build key via key_fn  │\n                │  2. limiter.enforce(key)  │\n                │                           │\n                │            │              │\n                │            ▼              │\n                │  ┌─────────────────────┐  │\n                │  │   RateLimiter       │  │\n                │  │   (TB or SW)        │  │\n                │  │                     │  │\n                │  │  translates         │  │\n                │  │  request → script   │  │\n                │  │  args; interprets   │  │\n                │  │  script result      │  │\n                │  └──────────┬──────────┘  │\n                │             ▼             │\n                │  ┌─────────────────────┐  │\n                │  │    Backend          │  │\n                │  │  (InMemory|Redis)   │  │\n                │  │                     │  │\n                │  │  atomic state       │  │\n                │  │  transition         │  │\n                │  └─────────────────────┘  │\n                │                           │\n                │  3. attach headers:       │\n                │     X-RateLimit-Limit     │\n                │     X-RateLimit-Remaining │\n                │     X-RateLimit-Reset     │\n                │     Retry-After (if 429)  │\n                └───────────┬───────────────┘\n                            │\n                            ▼\n                     downstream app\n```\n\nThe limiter never talks to Redis directly via multiple commands. For\nthe Redis backend, a single Lua script encapsulates *read →\ncompute → write* so it is trivially atomic. Clock is read inside Lua\n(`redis.call(\'TIME\')`), making the Redis server the authority.\n\n## State layout\n\n### Token bucket\n\nRedis key stores a HASH:\n```\nHSET  rl:tb:<key>  tokens  <float>   last_refill_ms  <int>\nEXPIRE rl:tb:<key> <ttl>\n```\n\nThe script:\n1. `HGETALL` → `(tokens, last_refill_ms)` or defaults.\n2. Compute server `now_ms` via `TIME`.\n3. `delta = max(0, now_ms - last_refill_ms)` (clock-skew clamp).\n4. `tokens = min(capacity, tokens + delta * refill_per_ms)`.\n5. If `tokens >= cost`: `tokens -= cost`, allowed=1.\n6. `HSET` back + `PEXPIRE`.\n7. Compute `retry_after_ms = ceil((cost - tokens) / refill_per_ms)`\n   when rejected.\n\n### Sliding window counter\n\nRedis key stores a HASH:\n```\nHSET  rl:sw:<key>  window_start_ms  <int>  count  <int>  prev_count  <int>\nPEXPIRE rl:sw:<key> <2 * period_ms>\n```\n\nThe script:\n1. `HGETALL` → `(window_start_ms, count, prev_count)` or defaults.\n2. `now_ms` via `TIME`.\n3. `elapsed = now_ms - window_start_ms`.\n4. If `elapsed >= 2 * period_ms`: `prev_count = 0; count = 0;\n   window_start = now_ms` (full reset — two windows idle).\n5. Else if `elapsed >= period_ms`: `prev_count = count; count = 0;\n   window_start += period_ms` (advance one window).\n6. `position_in_window = (now_ms - window_start_ms) / period_ms`\n   clamped to `[0, 1]`.\n7. `estimated = prev_count * (1 - position_in_window) + count`.\n8. If `estimated + cost <= capacity`: `count += cost`, allowed=1.\n9. `reset_ts = window_start_ms + period_ms`.\n\n## Concurrency\n\n- **Single Redis primary** — `EVAL` on Redis is strictly serialized,\n  so two `enforce` calls on the same key can never observe each\n  other\'s half-applied state. No lost updates, no over-grant.\n- **In-memory backend** — uses a `threading.Lock` per `Backend`\n  instance, plus a `Condition` guard around the shared dict to keep\n  insertion and read of a new key atomic. The async path\n  (`aenforce`) uses the same lock because `InMemoryBackend` is only\n  meaningful in single-process deployments.\n- **Atomicity test** — the concurrency test spawns 200 threads, each\n  of which calls `enforce` on the same key with `cost=1` against a\n  limiter of `capacity=50`. Asserted invariant: exactly 50 allowed,\n  never 51.\n\n## Failure modes and degradation\n\n| failure                          | default behaviour                                       |\n|----------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|\n| Redis unreachable (conn refused) | `fail_open=True` for middleware → allow, mark remaining=-1; `fail_open=False` for decorator → reject with 1s retry-after |\n| Redis script LOAD race           | `redis-py`\'s `Script` helper re-loads on `NOSCRIPT`     |\n| Redis returns malformed reply    | treated as failure per the `fail_open` policy; logged    |\n| Caller\'s clock skewed forward    | stored `last_refill_ms > now_ms`; script clamps `elapsed=0` — no free tokens |\n| Caller\'s clock skewed backward   | impossible: script uses server clock, ignores caller    |\n| Hot-key starvation               | Lua script is ~200ns on modern Redis; throughput bound is the Redis itself, not the algorithm |\n| Capacity=1 edge                  | unit-tested explicitly — must allow exactly one token per full refill interval |\n| Decorator re-entry               | `@rate_limit` uses `contextvars` to skip re-checking when the same key is already in-flight within the same logical call (idempotency within a request). Off by default; opt-in via `reentrant=True` |\n\n## Degradation strategy\n\nThe `RedisBackend` has a single `fail_open` knob. When `True`, any\nconnection or script error is swallowed and a synthetic "allowed"\n`Decision` is returned with `remaining=-1` and `retry_after_ms=0`.\nWhen `False`, errors produce a rejecting `Decision` with\n`retry_after_ms=1000`.\n\nWe deliberately do *not* build a local fallback cache that takes over\nduring an outage. That path is subtle (the local cache grants against\nlocal state only, so N workers collectively over-grant by a factor of\nN) and the operator is better served by an explicit `fail_open=True`\ndecision plus alerting on the `remaining=-1` signal.\n\nLog noise is suppressed to at most one warning per 60-second window\nper backend instance, so an hour-long Redis outage does not\noverwrite production logs.\n\n## Extensibility\n\n`Backend` is a Protocol; supplying a memcached, DynamoDB, or\nCloudflare-KV backend means implementing two methods:\n`token_bucket(...)` and `sliding_window(...)`. The limiters delegate\nalgorithm details to the backend so that each backend can implement\nthem in its native atomic primitive (CAS, conditional-update, Lua).\nNew algorithms are added by subclassing `RateLimiter` and teaching\neach backend a new method; this is deliberate — atomic primitives\ndon\'t compose, so we refuse to pretend they do by putting the algo\ninto pure Python on top of a generic "get/set" backend.\n\n## Operational caveats\n\n- Keys should include tenant and scope, e.g. `"tenant:42:login"`.\n- Use different limiter instances (or different key prefixes) for\n  unrelated quotas; do not multiplex them on a single key.\n- The Redis backend requires `EVAL` permission. Managed services\n  that disable `EVAL` (e.g. some Memorystore tiers) are not\n  supported.\n- Tests rely on `fakeredis`, which re-implements Redis in Python\n  including `EVAL`.\n')
Now the implementation. Let me start with the core types.  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/ratelimit/types.py', content='"""Core value types shared by limiters, backends and wrappers."""\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\n\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True, slots=True)\nclass Decision:\n    """Result of a single rate-limit check.\n\n    Attributes\n    ----------\n    allowed:\n        ``True`` iff the caller may proceed with the request.\n    retry_after_ms:\n        Milliseconds the caller should wait before retrying.  Zero\n        when ``allowed`` is true.\n    remaining:\n        Best-effort remaining capacity for the key *after* this\n        decision.  ``-1`` signals "unknown" (e.g. fail-open path).\n    reset_ts:\n        Unix timestamp (seconds) at which the window or bucket will\n        be fully refilled.  Suitable for the ``X-RateLimit-Reset``\n        HTTP header.\n    """\n\n    allowed: bool\n    retry_after_ms: int\n    remaining: int\n    reset_ts: int\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/ratelimit/backends.py', content='"""Backend abstraction plus in-memory and Redis implementations.\n\nA backend encapsulates the *atomic* state transition required by each\nalgorithm.  Algorithms (in :mod:`ratelimit.limiters`) stay thin — they\ntranslate high-level arguments (``capacity``, ``period``, ``cost``) into\na backend call and wrap the numeric result in a :class:`Decision`.\n\nThis split is deliberate: atomic primitives don\'t compose, so we keep\neach algorithm\'s atomic unit local to the backend that can implement\nit natively (CAS, Lua, conditional update, ...).\n"""\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\nimport math\nimport threading\nimport time\nfrom typing import Protocol, Tuple\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger("ratelimit.backend")\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Protocol\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nclass Backend(Protocol):\n    """Atomic state transitions for each supported algorithm.\n\n    Every method returns a tuple of ``(allowed, remaining,\n    retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s)`` so the limiter layer only has to\n    wrap it in a :class:`Decision`.\n    """\n\n    def token_bucket(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        capacity: float,\n        refill_per_sec: float,\n        cost: float,\n    ) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        """Consume ``cost`` tokens from a token bucket identified by\n        ``key``.  Must be atomic across concurrent callers."""\n        ...\n\n    def sliding_window(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        capacity: int,\n        period_ms: int,\n        cost: int,\n    ) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        """Consume ``cost`` units from a sliding-window counter.\n        Must be atomic across concurrent callers."""\n        ...\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# In-memory backend\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nclass InMemoryBackend:\n    """Single-process backend backed by a dict and a re-entrant lock.\n\n    Concurrency-safe for threads and the asyncio event loop (all\n    critical sections are short and CPU-bound).  Not suitable for\n    multi-process use — N workers with their own backend each grant\n    up to ``capacity`` and collectively over-grant by a factor of N.\n    """\n\n    def __init__(self, *, clock=time.monotonic) -> None:\n        self._state: dict[str, dict] = {}\n        self._lock = threading.Lock()\n        self._clock = clock  # seconds, monotonic\n\n    # -- token bucket -----------------------------------------------------\n\n    def token_bucket(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        capacity: float,\n        refill_per_sec: float,\n        cost: float,\n    ) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        if capacity <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("capacity must be > 0")\n        if refill_per_sec <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("refill_per_sec must be > 0")\n        if cost < 0:\n            raise ValueError("cost must be >= 0")\n\n        now = self._clock()\n        storage_key = ("tb", key)\n        with self._lock:\n            entry = self._state.get(storage_key)\n            if entry is None:\n                tokens = float(capacity)\n                last = now\n            else:\n                tokens = entry["tokens"]\n                last = entry["last"]\n                # clock-skew clamp: ignore "future" timestamps\n                elapsed = max(0.0, now - last)\n                tokens = min(float(capacity), tokens + elapsed * refill_per_sec)\n                last = now\n\n            if tokens + 1e-9 >= cost:\n                tokens -= cost\n                allowed = 1\n                retry_after_ms = 0\n            else:\n                allowed = 0\n                deficit = cost - tokens\n                retry_after_ms = int(math.ceil(deficit / refill_per_sec * 1000.0))\n\n            self._state[storage_key] = {"tokens": tokens, "last": last}\n\n            # reset_ts: when the bucket is full again (wall-clock seconds)\n            deficit_to_full = max(0.0, capacity - tokens)\n            seconds_to_full = deficit_to_full / refill_per_sec\n            reset_ts_s = int(time.time() + seconds_to_full)\n            remaining = int(math.floor(tokens))\n            return allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s\n\n    # -- sliding window counter ------------------------------------------\n\n    def sliding_window(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        capacity: int,\n        period_ms: int,\n        cost: int,\n    ) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        if capacity <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("capacity must be > 0")\n        if period_ms <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("period_ms must be > 0")\n        if cost < 0:\n            raise ValueError("cost must be >= 0")\n\n        now_ms = int(self._clock() * 1000)\n        storage_key = ("sw", key)\n        with self._lock:\n            entry = self._state.get(storage_key)\n            if entry is None:\n                window_start = now_ms\n                count = 0\n                prev_count = 0\n            else:\n                window_start = entry["window_start"]\n                count = entry["count"]\n                prev_count = entry["prev_count"]\n                elapsed = now_ms - window_start\n                if elapsed < 0:\n                    # stored future stamp — treat as "no progress"\n                    elapsed = 0\n                if elapsed >= 2 * period_ms:\n                    window_start = now_ms\n                    count = 0\n                    prev_count = 0\n                elif elapsed >= period_ms:\n                    prev_count = count\n                    count = 0\n                    window_start = window_start + period_ms\n\n            pos = (now_ms - window_start) / period_ms\n            if pos < 0:\n                pos = 0.0\n            if pos > 1:\n                pos = 1.0\n            estimated = prev_count * (1.0 - pos) + count\n\n            if estimated + cost <= capacity:\n                count += cost\n                allowed = 1\n                retry_after_ms = 0\n            else:\n                allowed = 0\n                # retry when enough of the prev window has "slid out"\n                # to admit the request: find the smallest dt such that\n                #   prev_count * (1 - (pos + dt)) + count + cost <= capacity\n                # solved for dt (in units of period):\n                over = estimated + cost - capacity\n                if prev_count > 0:\n                    dt_periods = over / prev_count\n                    retry_after_ms = int(math.ceil(dt_periods * period_ms))\n                else:\n                    # only way forward is the current window to end\n                    retry_after_ms = max(1, period_ms - (now_ms - window_start))\n\n            self._state[storage_key] = {\n                "window_start": window_start,\n                "count": count,\n                "prev_count": prev_count,\n            }\n            reset_ts_s = int((window_start + period_ms) / 1000)\n            remaining = max(0, int(capacity - math.ceil(estimated + (cost if allowed else 0))))\n            return allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s\n\n    # -- test / admin helpers --------------------------------------------\n\n    def reset(self, key: str | None = None) -> None:\n        with self._lock:\n            if key is None:\n                self._state.clear()\n            else:\n                self._state.pop(("tb", key), None)\n                self._state.pop(("sw", key), None)\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Redis backend\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n# Lua script for token bucket.\n#\n# KEYS[1] = bucket key\n# ARGV[1] = capacity (float)\n# ARGV[2] = refill_per_sec (float)\n# ARGV[3] = cost (float)\n# ARGV[4] = ttl_ms (int) — key expiry\n#\n# Returns: {allowed (0/1), remaining (int), retry_after_ms (int), reset_ts_s (int)}\n_TOKEN_BUCKET_LUA = """\nlocal key = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity      = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal refill_per_s  = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost          = tonumber(ARGV[3])\nlocal ttl_ms        = tonumber(ARGV[4])\n\nlocal t = redis.call(\'TIME\')\nlocal now_ms = (tonumber(t[1]) * 1000) + math.floor(tonumber(t[2]) / 1000)\n\nlocal data = redis.call(\'HMGET\', key, \'tokens\', \'last_ms\')\nlocal tokens = tonumber(data[1])\nlocal last_ms = tonumber(data[2])\n\nif tokens == nil then\n    tokens = capacity\n    last_ms = now_ms\nend\n\nlocal elapsed_ms = now_ms - last_ms\nif elapsed_ms < 0 then elapsed_ms = 0 end   -- clock-skew clamp\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + (elapsed_ms / 1000.0) * refill_per_s)\nlast_ms = now_ms\n\nlocal allowed = 0\nlocal retry_after_ms = 0\nif tokens + 1e-9 >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nelse\n    local deficit = cost - tokens\n    retry_after_ms = math.ceil(deficit / refill_per_s * 1000)\nend\n\nredis.call(\'HMSET\', key, \'tokens\', tokens, \'last_ms\', last_ms)\nredis.call(\'PEXPIRE\', key, ttl_ms)\n\nlocal deficit_to_full = capacity - tokens\nif deficit_to_full < 0 then deficit_to_full = 0 end\nlocal seconds_to_full = deficit_to_full / refill_per_s\nlocal reset_ts_s = math.floor((now_ms / 1000) + seconds_to_full)\nlocal remaining = math.floor(tokens)\nreturn {allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s}\n"""\n\n\n# Lua script for sliding-window counter.\n#\n# KEYS[1] = window key\n# ARGV[1] = capacity (int)\n# ARGV[2] = period_ms (int)\n# ARGV[3] = cost (int)\n# ARGV[4] = ttl_ms (int)\n_SLIDING_WINDOW_LUA = """\nlocal key = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity  = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal period_ms = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost      = tonumber(ARGV[3])\nlocal ttl_ms    = tonumber(ARGV[4])\n\nlocal t = redis.call(\'TIME\')\nlocal now_ms = (tonumber(t[1]) * 1000) + math.floor(tonumber(t[2]) / 1000)\n\nlocal data = redis.call(\'HMGET\', key, \'window_start\', \'count\', \'prev_count\')\nlocal window_start = tonumber(data[1])\nlocal count        = tonumber(data[2])\nlocal prev_count   = tonumber(data[3])\n\nif window_start == nil then\n    window_start = now_ms\n    count = 0\n    prev_count = 0\nend\n\nlocal elapsed = now_ms - window_start\nif elapsed < 0 then elapsed = 0 end\nif elapsed >= 2 * period_ms then\n    window_start = now_ms\n    count = 0\n    prev_count = 0\nelseif elapsed >= period_ms then\n    prev_count = count\n    count = 0\n    window_start = window_start + period_ms\nend\n\nlocal pos = (now_ms - window_start) / period_ms\nif pos < 0 then pos = 0 end\nif pos > 1 then pos = 1 end\nlocal estimated = prev_count * (1.0 - pos) + count\n\nlocal allowed = 0\nlocal retry_after_ms = 0\nif estimated + cost <= capacity then\n    count = count + cost\n    allowed = 1\nelse\n    local over = estimated + cost - capacity\n    if prev_count > 0 then\n        retry_after_ms = math.ceil((over / prev_count) * period_ms)\n    else\n        retry_after_ms = period_ms - (now_ms - window_start)\n        if retry_after_ms < 1 then retry_after_ms = 1 end\n    end\nend\n\nredis.call(\'HMSET\', key, \'window_start\', window_start, \'count\', count, \'prev_count\', prev_count)\nredis.call(\'PEXPIRE\', key, ttl_ms)\n\nlocal reset_ts_s = math.floor((window_start + period_ms) / 1000)\nlocal used = estimated\nif allowed == 1 then used = used + cost end\nlocal remaining = capacity - math.ceil(used)\nif remaining < 0 then remaining = 0 end\nreturn {allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s}\n"""\n\n\nclass RedisBackend:\n    """Redis-backed backend using atomic Lua scripts.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    redis_client:\n        A ``redis.Redis`` (or ``fakeredis.FakeRedis``) instance.\n    key_prefix:\n        Prefix prepended to every key (defaults to ``"rl:"``).  Pick a\n        unique prefix per logical limiter to avoid key collisions\n        between algorithms or environments.\n    fail_open:\n        If true, Redis errors produce an allowed :class:`Decision`\n        with ``remaining=-1``; if false, a rejecting decision with\n        ``retry_after_ms=1000``.\n    ttl_ms:\n        TTL applied to each key on every touch.  Defaults to\n        ``max(period, 10 * capacity / refill)`` per call.  An explicit\n        value overrides the per-call heuristic.\n    log_backoff_s:\n        Minimum seconds between repeated warning log entries when\n        Redis is unreachable.\n    """\n\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        redis_client,\n        *,\n        key_prefix: str = "rl:",\n        fail_open: bool = False,\n        ttl_ms: int | None = None,\n        log_backoff_s: float = 60.0,\n    ) -> None:\n        self._redis = redis_client\n        self._prefix = key_prefix\n        self._fail_open = fail_open\n        self._forced_ttl_ms = ttl_ms\n        self._log_backoff_s = log_backoff_s\n        self._last_warn_ts = 0.0\n        self._warn_lock = threading.Lock()\n\n        # Register scripts once; redis-py\'s Script helper transparently\n        # re-loads on NOSCRIPT.\n        self._tb_script = self._redis.register_script(_TOKEN_BUCKET_LUA)\n        self._sw_script = self._redis.register_script(_SLIDING_WINDOW_LUA)\n\n    # -- helpers ----------------------------------------------------------\n\n    def _maybe_warn(self, exc: Exception) -> None:\n        now = time.monotonic()\n        with self._warn_lock:\n            if now - self._last_warn_ts >= self._log_backoff_s:\n                self._last_warn_ts = now\n                logger.warning("ratelimit: redis backend unavailable: %r", exc)\n\n    def _fail(self) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        if self._fail_open:\n            return (1, -1, 0, int(time.time()))\n        return (0, 0, 1000, int(time.time()) + 1)\n\n    # -- token bucket -----------------------------------------------------\n\n    def token_bucket(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        capacity: float,\n        refill_per_sec: float,\n        cost: float,\n    ) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        if capacity <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("capacity must be > 0")\n        if refill_per_sec <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("refill_per_sec must be > 0")\n        if cost < 0:\n            raise ValueError("cost must be >= 0")\n\n        full_key = f"{self._prefix}tb:{key}"\n        if self._forced_ttl_ms is not None:\n            ttl_ms = self._forced_ttl_ms\n        else:\n            # keep the key long enough that a full refill + margin fits.\n            ttl_ms = max(10_000, int((capacity / refill_per_sec) * 10_000))\n        try:\n            raw = self._tb_script(\n                keys=[full_key],\n                args=[capacity, refill_per_sec, cost, ttl_ms],\n            )\n        except Exception as exc:  # pragma: no cover — exercised in tests\n            self._maybe_warn(exc)\n            return self._fail()\n        allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s = raw\n        return (int(allowed), int(remaining), int(retry_after_ms), int(reset_ts_s))\n\n    # -- sliding window ---------------------------------------------------\n\n    def sliding_window(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        capacity: int,\n        period_ms: int,\n        cost: int,\n    ) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n        if capacity <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("capacity must be > 0")\n        if period_ms <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("period_ms must be > 0")\n        if cost < 0:\n            raise ValueError("cost must be >= 0")\n\n        full_key = f"{self._prefix}sw:{key}"\n        if self._forced_ttl_ms is not None:\n            ttl_ms = self._forced_ttl_ms\n        else:\n            ttl_ms = max(10_000, 2 * period_ms)\n        try:\n            raw = self._sw_script(\n                keys=[full_key],\n                args=[capacity, period_ms, cost, ttl_ms],\n            )\n        except Exception as exc:  # pragma: no cover\n            self._maybe_warn(exc)\n            return self._fail()\n        allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s = raw\n        return (int(allowed), int(remaining), int(retry_after_ms), int(reset_ts_s))\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/ratelimit/limiters.py', content='"""Rate-limiter abstract base class and algorithm implementations."""\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n\nfrom .backends import Backend, InMemoryBackend\nfrom .types import Decision\n\n\nclass RateLimiter(ABC):\n    """Abstract base class: computes a :class:`Decision` for a key.\n\n    Subclasses implement :meth:`enforce`.  The base class stores the\n    chosen backend and the nominal ``limit``/``period`` used by the\n    middleware to populate ``X-RateLimit-Limit``.\n    """\n\n    def __init__(self, *, backend: Backend | None = None) -> None:\n        self.backend: Backend = backend if backend is not None else InMemoryBackend()\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def enforce(self, key: str, cost: float = 1) -> Decision:\n        """Atomically attempt to consume ``cost`` units for ``key``."""\n\n    # Informational — used by middleware for headers.\n    @property\n    @abstractmethod\n    def limit(self) -> int:\n        ...\n\n\nclass TokenBucketLimiter(RateLimiter):\n    """Classic token bucket.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    capacity:\n        Maximum number of tokens the bucket holds; also the maximum\n        burst size.\n    refill_per_sec:\n        Tokens regenerated per second.  The sustained rate.\n    backend:\n        Backend to use.  Defaults to :class:`InMemoryBackend`.\n    """\n\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        capacity: float,\n        refill_per_sec: float,\n        *,\n        backend: Backend | None = None,\n    ) -> None:\n        super().__init__(backend=backend)\n        if capacity <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("capacity must be > 0")\n        if refill_per_sec <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("refill_per_sec must be > 0")\n        self.capacity = float(capacity)\n        self.refill_per_sec = float(refill_per_sec)\n\n    @property\n    def limit(self) -> int:\n        return int(self.capacity)\n\n    def enforce(self, key: str, cost: float = 1) -> Decision:\n        if cost < 0:\n            raise ValueError("cost must be >= 0")\n        allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s = self.backend.token_bucket(\n            key, self.capacity, self.refill_per_sec, float(cost)\n        )\n        return Decision(\n            allowed=bool(allowed),\n            retry_after_ms=int(retry_after_ms),\n            remaining=int(remaining),\n            reset_ts=int(reset_ts_s),\n        )\n\n\nclass SlidingWindowLimiter(RateLimiter):\n    """Sliding-window counter (weighted previous + current window).\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    capacity:\n        Maximum units admitted in any trailing ``period`` window.\n    period_ms:\n        Window size in milliseconds.\n    backend:\n        Backend to use.  Defaults to :class:`InMemoryBackend`.\n    """\n\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        capacity: int,\n        period_ms: int,\n        *,\n        backend: Backend | None = None,\n    ) -> None:\n        super().__init__(backend=backend)\n        if capacity <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("capacity must be > 0")\n        if period_ms <= 0:\n            raise ValueError("period_ms must be > 0")\n        self.capacity = int(capacity)\n        self.period_ms = int(period_ms)\n\n    @property\n    def limit(self) -> int:\n        return self.capacity\n\n    def enforce(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Decision:\n        if cost < 0:\n            raise ValueError("cost must be >= 0")\n        allowed, remaining, retry_after_ms, reset_ts_s = self.backend.sliding_window(\n            key, self.capacity, self.period_ms, int(cost)\n        )\n        return Decision(\n            allowed=bool(allowed),\n            retry_after_ms=int(retry_after_ms),\n            remaining=int(remaining),\n            reset_ts=int(reset_ts_s),\n        )\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/ratelimit/decorator.py', content='"""Decorator wrapper for function-level rate limiting."""\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport asyncio\nimport contextvars\nimport functools\nfrom typing import Any, Callable\n\nfrom .limiters import RateLimiter\nfrom .types import Decision\n\n\nclass RateLimitExceeded(Exception):\n    """Raised by ``@rate_limit`` when a call is rejected."""\n\n    def __init__(self, decision: Decision, key: str) -> None:\n        super().__init__(\n            f"rate limit exceeded for key={key!r}; "\n            f"retry after {decision.retry_after_ms} ms"\n        )\n        self.decision = decision\n        self.key = key\n\n\n# Context variable tracking keys currently in flight for re-entrancy\n# detection.  A `frozenset[str]` so nested calls can extend without\n# mutating the parent\'s set.\n_inflight_keys: contextvars.ContextVar[frozenset[str]] = contextvars.ContextVar(\n    "ratelimit_inflight_keys", default=frozenset()\n)\n\n\ndef rate_limit(\n    limiter: RateLimiter,\n    key_fn: Callable[..., str],\n    *,\n    cost: float = 1,\n    reentrant: bool = False,\n    on_rejected: Callable[[Decision, str], Any] | None = None,\n) -> Callable[[Callable[..., Any]], Callable[..., Any]]:\n    """Decorate a function with rate limiting.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    limiter:\n        The :class:`RateLimiter` that makes the decision.\n    key_fn:\n        Callable receiving the wrapped function\'s ``*args, **kwargs``\n        and returning the bucket key.\n    cost:\n        Units consumed per call.  Default 1.\n    reentrant:\n        If true, a call whose key is already "in flight" higher up\n        the call stack is admitted without consulting the limiter.\n        Useful for recursion / wrapper composition where re-checking\n        the same key would double-charge.\n    on_rejected:\n        Optional callback invoked instead of raising\n        :class:`RateLimitExceeded`.  If it returns a value that value\n        is returned from the wrapped function; if it returns ``None``\n        the exception is still raised.\n    """\n\n    def decorate(fn: Callable[..., Any]) -> Callable[..., Any]:\n        if asyncio.iscoroutinefunction(fn):\n\n            @functools.wraps(fn)\n            async def async_wrapper(*args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any:\n                key = key_fn(*args, **kwargs)\n                inflight = _inflight_keys.get()\n                if reentrant and key in inflight:\n                    return await fn(*args, **kwargs)\n\n                decision = limiter.enforce(key, cost=cost)\n                if not decision.allowed:\n                    if on_rejected is not None:\n                        result = on_rejected(decision, key)\n                        if result is not None:\n                            return result\n                    raise RateLimitExceeded(decision, key)\n\n                token = _inflight_keys.set(inflight | {key})\n                try:\n                    return await fn(*args, **kwargs)\n                finally:\n                    _inflight_keys.reset(token)\n\n            return async_wrapper\n\n        @functools.wraps(fn)\n        def sync_wrapper(*args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any:\n            key = key_fn(*args, **kwargs)\n            inflight = _inflight_keys.get()\n            if reentrant and key in inflight:\n                return fn(*args, **kwargs)\n\n            decision = limiter.enforce(key, cost=cost)\n            if not decision.allowed:\n                if on_rejected is not None:\n                    result = on_rejected(decision, key)\n                    if result is not None:\n                        return result\n                raise RateLimitExceeded(decision, key)\n\n            token = _inflight_keys.set(inflight | {key})\n            try:\n                return fn(*args, **kwargs)\n            finally:\n                _inflight_keys.reset(token)\n\n        return sync_wrapper\n\n    return decorate\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-opus/ratelimit/middleware.py', content='"""ASGI middleware for FastAPI / Starlette.\n\nAdds the four standard rate-limit response headers\n(``X-RateLimit-Limit``, ``X-RateLimit-Remaining``,\n``X-RateLimit-Reset``, ``Retry-After``) and returns HTTP 429 when a\nrequest is rejected.\n"""\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom typing import Any, Awaitable, Callable, Mapping\n\nfrom .limiters import RateLimiter\nfrom .types import Decision\n\nScope = Mapping[str, Any]\nReceive = Callable[[], Awaitable[Mapping[str, Any]]]\nSend = Callable[[Mapping[str, Any]], Awaitable[None]]\n\n\ndef _default_key_fn(scope: Scope) -> str:\n    """Default key: remote client IP + method + path.\n\n    Production users should override this to include the\n    authenticated principal.\n    """\n    client = scope.get("client")\n    ip = client[0] if client else "unknown"\n    method = scope.get("method", "GET")\n    path = scope.get("path", "/")\n    return f"{ip}:{method}:{path}"\n\n\nclass RateLimitMiddleware:\n    """ASGI middleware enforcing a :class:`RateLimiter`.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    app:\n        The downstream ASGI app.\n    limiter:\n        The limiter used for every request.\n    key_fn:\n        Callable receiving the ASGI ``scope`` and returning the\n        bucket key.  Defaults to ``ip:method:path``.\n    cost:\n        Units consumed per request.  Default 1.\n    apply_to:\n        Iterable of scope types to limit (default ``("http",)`` only\n        — websockets pass through unchanged).\n    """\n\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        app: Any,\n        limiter: RateLimiter,\n        *,\n        key_fn: Callable[[Scope], str] = _default_key_fn,\n        cost: float = 1,\n        apply_to: tuple[str, ...] = ("http",),\n    ) -> None:\n        self.app = app\n        self.limiter = limiter\n        self.key_fn = key_fn\n        self.cost = cost\n        self.apply_to = tuple(apply_to)\n\n    async def __call__(self, scope: Scope, receive: Receive, send: Send) -> None:\n        if scope.get("type") not in self.apply_to:\n            await self.app(scope, receive, send)\n            return\n\n        key = self.key_fn(scope)\n        decision = self.limiter.enforce(key, cost=self.cost)\n\n        if not decision.allowed:\n            await _send_429(decision, self.limiter.limit, send)\n            return\n\n        # Wrap `send` so we can inject headers on the outgoing response.\n        async def send_with_headers(message: Mapping[str, Any]) -> None:\n            if message["type"] == "http.response.start":\n                message = dict(message)\n                headers = list(message.get("headers") or [])\n                _extend_rate_headers(headers, decision, self.limiter.limit)\n                message["headers"] = headers\n            await send(message)\n\n        await self.app(scope, receive, send_with_headers)\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# helpers\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\ndef _extend_rate_headers(\n    headers: list[tuple[bytes, bytes]],\n    decision: Decision,\n    limit: int,\n) -> None:\n    remaining = decision.remaining if decision.remaining >= 0 else 0\n    headers.append((b"x-ratelimit-limit", str(limit).encode("ascii")))\n    headers.append((b"x-ratelimit-remaining", str(remaining).encode("ascii")))\n    headers.append((b"x-ratelimit-reset", str(decision.reset_ts).encode("ascii")))\n    if decision.retry_after_ms > 0:\n        # Retry-After is seconds in the HTTP spec; round up so we\n        # never under-shoot the backend\'s calculation.\n        retry_s = max(1, (decision.retry_after_ms + 999) // 1000)\n        headers.append((b"retry-after", str(retry_s).encode("ascii")))\n\n\nasync def _send_429(decision: Decision, limit: int, send: Send) -> None:\n    headers: list[tuple[bytes, bytes]] = [\n        (b"content-type", b"text/plain; charset=utf-8"),\n    ]\n    _extend_rate_headers(headers, decision, limit)\n    body = b"Too Many Requests\\n"\n    await send(\n        {\n            "type": "http.response.start",\n            "status": 429,\n            "headers": headers,\n        }\n    )\n    await send(\n        {\n            "type": "http.response.body",\n            "body": body,\n            "more_body": False,\n        }\n    )\n')
